      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense, but it still feels a bit weird. i read somewhere that einstein called it \"spooky action at a distance\" because it seems to defy how things usually work. why exactly did he think it was \"spooky\" though? like what's the part that's actually so unsettling about it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Einstein referred to quantum entanglement as \"spooky action at a distance\" because it seemingly contradicts the principles of classical physics and his own theory of relativity, which suggests that nothing in the universe can travel faster than the speed of light. The \"spooky\" part lies in the instantaneous nature of the entanglement effect: a change in one particle's state can instantly influence its partner, seemingly bypassing the time it would take for a signal to travel at the speed of light. This challenges the causal order of events and raises questions about the deeper nature of reality, since it implies a kind of instantaneous connection independent from the limits of cause and effect as understood in the classical world.",
