    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i get that part. it's just hard to wrap my head around how something can happen \"instantly\" without any physical connection or signal being sent between them. it feels almost like there's some hidden mechanism or something \"behind the scenes\" making it happen. is there any way scientists have tried to explain that hidden connection, or is it just accepted as a fundamental weirdness of the universe?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The current understanding of quantum entanglement hinges on the probability-based nature of quantum mechanics and doesn't involve \"hidden messages\" or physical signals being sent between particles. Scientists don't hold a hidden mechanism responsible for the instant connection but rather attribute it to the entangled particles existing in a unified quantum state. Despite being seemingly instantaneous and \"spooky\", it can be explained by the wave-like properties of particles as described by the quantum field theory, where the state of one particle is intrinsically linked to the state of the other. In essence, it's the predetermined correlations established when particles become entangled, manifesting as correlations when measured, without the necessity of a direct cause-and-effect relationship observable in the classical world. This is not so much a matter of \"hidden connections\" but rather about the fundamental and non-intuitive way in which quantum states are correlated, an aspect of quantum theory that continues to puzzle and inspire new research even today.",
      "source": "target",
